 testing was central to his eventual pardon, such tests would never have occurred without an unusually talented and committed legal team and without a series of incidents that are best described as pure luck.Margaret Edds makes the chilling argument that some other “expendable men” almost certainly have been less fortunate than Washington. This, she writes, is “the secret, shameful underbelly” of America's retention of capital punishment. Such wrongful executions may not happen often, but anyone who doubts that innocent people have been executed in the United States should remember the remarkable series of events necessary to save Earl Washington Jr. from such a fate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American prisonersvBiography. 0aCapital punishmentxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aDNA fingerprintingzUnited States. 0aDeath row inmateszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited States. 0aPeople with mental disabilities and crimezUnited StatesvBiography. 7aLAW / Civil Law.2bisacsh  a19-year-old.  a1983.  aCulpeper.  aEarl.  aExpendable.  aJr.  aVirginia.  aWashington.  ablack.  acase.  aconvicted.  aexecution.  aexplores.  afarm.  ahand.  amentally.  amother.  amurder.  anear.  arape.  aretarded.  athree.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814722794423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814722794.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STM